FreeCAD <www.freecadweb.org> Meet the incredible free CAD and parametric 3D modeler with a Python interface. On the Python console you can see all the equivalent commands of the ones you "manualy" made on the interface so as to learn how to automate actions. On the "Macro" window there is an editor to create, salve and execute longer scripts. On the right sise example a slab with a grid of cylindrical holes. Join the community using it, asking questions at the discussion forum <forum.freecad.org>, translating, documenting and sharing your designs!

py5 <py5coding.org> is a library that can make use of vocabulary and graphics infrastructure from Processing <processing.org> together with the Python <python.org> programming language. Processing is a Free and Open Source (FLOSS) programming platform, widely used by artists and designers, as well as for teaching programming in a visual context. It allows you to generate interactive software with the most diverse purposes and visual interfaces, as well as exporting bitmap/raster images (like PNG and JPG), animations or 2D and 3D vector files (like PDF and SVG, among others). The community enjoys a rich ecosystem of people who produce resources such as teaching examples and freely shared code libraries. Bellow you can see an example of code using py5, it generates the drawing on the left, written in a conventional Python style starting with the import py5 instruction, on the right, the same example, but written in a more concise style called imported mode, made for begginers, using the thonny-py5mode plug-in inside Thonny IDE. import py5 def setup(): py5.size(800, 800) py5.background(200) py5.no_fill() py5.no_loop() py5.random_seed(1) def draw(): py5.background(200) x = y = py5.width / 2 recursive_polygons(x, y, py5.width / 4) def recursive_polygons(xo, yo, r, n=6): a = py5.TWO_PI / n pontos = [(xo + r * py5.cos(i * a), yo + r * py5.sin(i * a)) for i in range(n)] sorteio = py5.random_choice((True, False)) w = py5.width if r > w / 10 or (sorteio and r > w / 200): for x, y in pontos: py5.stroke_weight(r / 50) py5.line(x, y, xo, yo) recursive_polygons(x, y, r / 2, n) else: py5.stroke_weight(r / 10) with py5.begin_closed_shape(): py5.vertices(pontos) def key_pressed(e): py5.save_frame('imagem.png') py5.redraw() py5.run_sketch()

O Thonny IDE <thonny.org> is a software development environment thought for beginners that comes with Python 3 already built-in, an open project that deserves your attention! If you install the thonny-py5mode in Thonny, this will install the py5 library, download and configure its dependencies (like the JDK) adding the py5 menu to make its use easier! Learn more at: <https://abav.lugaralgum.com/como-instalar-py5/index-EN.html>

An excerpt of the Processing Foundation mission: [...] to promote software learning within the arts, artistic learning within technology-related fields, and to celebrate the diverse communities that make these fields vibrant, liberatory, and innovative. Our goal is to support people of all backgrounds in learning how to program and make creative work with code, especially those who might not otherwise have access to tools and resources. [...] Processing software is originaly based in the Java programming language, but today there are many projects that develop the ideas of Processing in other languages, like p5js with Javascript (accessible via Python/pyodide with pyp5js), Processing Python mode (Jython 2.7), JRubyArt with Ruby, and more recently p5py and py5 with Python 3. Furthermore many other projects were influenced by Processing, like OpenFrameworks based on C++, OPENRNDR in Kotlin, drawbot, nodebox, shoebot <shoebot.net> based in Python. Read more about Python drawing options at: <https://github.com/villares/resources-for-teaching-programming>
